snippet.textDisplay:
I've been thinking about this current situation and, now hear me out, I think this could be a legal issue...business wise. Here's how:

1.) It's no secret -- and I think all fans would agree-- that the channel "Danplan" was portrayed to us as though it belonged to Daniel, Stephen and Hosuh (all three men). We see clear instances of this in videos like: the fan mail and p.o box video, the "how we first met" video, the "incorrect danplan quotes" video, the pranking hosuh videos, the RPG opening credits in the 5th rpg video, and the "is it wrong to sell merch" video (to name a few). We also see this in the danplan merch which only have Daniel, Stephen and Hosuh drawn on them, and with the "knives are too informal" shirt that was titled as "stephen shirt" in the danplan merch store (I bought this shirt and still have the receipt that calls it that).
So it's not far fetched to say that Danplan, as a channel, was wildly believed by a majority of the audience/public to belong to Daniel, Stephen, and Hosuh...at least due to how the channel was marketed/advertised.

2.) From the existence of reason number one, it's not farfetched to say that (Danplan TM) marketed Stephen's personality/character on the channel for profit. Again, the most clearest instance would be the merch, but we can also use their videos which garnered AD revenue (such as the videos I stated above as well as a lot of their more popular videos like the zombie apocalypse ones, the psychopath video, and also videos like the dating advice video or love language video). With this, in addition to the marketing of Danplan as a channel that includes the prime members: Stephen, Daniel and Hosuh, a claim can be made that Stephen was intentionally marketed as a Danplan member and his character was used for major profit on the channel (e.g his statement "knives are too informal" being put on a shirt and sold for profit in the Danplan merch store).

3.) With the first 2 statements in mind, I want to make a claim that in this way, Stephen was used for a large part of Danplan's financial profit as well as success. Unquestionably, he was marketed for 5 years. So he clearly deserved more than 1% of the channel's monetary gains and he clearly should have a share in the channel (since he's marketed as a vital member and used extensively for entertainment and profit on the channel).

4.) The fact that, ever since the channel became monetized and started to gain revenue, Daniel chose to pay Stephen only 1% of the channel's profit, as well as chose to not place Stephen as a member and/or shareholder of the channel, but still continued to advertise him as such and market him for the channel's success and monetary gain....that fact is shady to say the least...and could be a legal issue. In short, Daniel owes Stephen a lot of money (if Stephen is recognized as a member and shareholder of the channel).

5.) This is were things get...sinister...
If Stephen is recognized by Daniel as a member of the channel, not only does he then receive a share of the channel's profits, but he can also discuss what percentage share he is to receive, as well as argue that Daniel is to reimburse him for the profit that wasn't paid to him prior (because he can argue that he was always a member in addition to being marketed for profit). Now, if Daniel fails to recognize Stephen as a member, and insists that Stephen had never been a member, only an employee that Daniel (and/or Hosuh, depending on if Josuh is considered a member ) had hired, then legally--and this is why I personally believe Dan stubbornly refused to recognize Stephen's efforts on the channel as "work" and refused to acknowledge Stephen's influence and impact on the channel's growth and financial success--legally, if Dan only ever acknowledged Stephen as an employee that was hired and did minimal work which had next to no impact or influence on the channel, that justifies Daniel "paying his employee" a wage that "fits the work the employee put in", and justifies Daniel blocking Stephen from having a share of the channel's profits from the start. By Dan stating that Stephen is only an employee, and has always only been just that, he can market Stephen for profit and keep that profit from Stephen without being liable to fraud.

6.) Fraud. That's the key word here. A case can be made that Stephen is a victim of fraudulent activity. And the only thing that protects Dan from being the one committing fraud is that (presumably) no formal contracts were signed (due to Stephen not viewing the YouTube thing as a business ). And because no contracts were signed which officially placed Stephen as a member/shareholder of the channel, Daniel, as (presumably ) the prime owner of Danplan under YouTube, can enact any title he wants onto Stephen's position on the channel. Although he marketed Stephen for profit and portrayed him as a prime/integral member of Danplan, Daniel didn't pay Stephen as though he was. Rather, and I think this is because Daniel knew Stephen didnt consider what he did on the channel through a business lens, he paid Stephen an extremely minimal amount...an amount you would pay an employee that had next to no influence or impact on his business ( e.g. an intern). By Dan refusing to acknowledge that he had advertised Stephen as a member and used him (his character and personas) for profit, that legally protects him from committing fraud against Stephen.

In the end, from a business as well as personal perspective, what Dan did was fucked up. In every way you look at this, Daniel took advantage of Stephen and abused the trust that their friendship had formed. And it is entirely possible that he did so knowingly and willingly (due to the fact that he was gipping Stephen from the start, and when Stephen confronted him about it, he doubled down and "legally justified" his mistreatment of Stephen by placing Stephen under the role of an employee who had little to no impact on Danplan's success.) I'm sorry Stephen. I really do hope this is not the case. But a case can be made here. I would really like to hear Daniel's perspective, but he'd have to be careful about what he says and many reasons he gives because if he does recognize Stephen as a member (as having a share on the channel), Daniel may be liable for commiting fraud...
